{"title_page": "Days and Clouds", "text_new": "{{short description|2007 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Days and Clouds\n| image          = Days and Clouds.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Silvio Soldini]]\n| producer       = Lionello Cerri\n| writer         = Silvio Soldini<br>[[Doriana Leondeff]]<br>[[Francesco Piccolo]]\n| starring       = [[Margherita Buy]]\n| music          = Giovanni Venosta\n| cinematography = Ramiro Civita\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2007|9|12|[[2007 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2007|10|26|Italy|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 118 minutes\n| country        = Italy\n| language       = Italian\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Days and Clouds''''' ({{lang-it|'''Giorni e nuvole'''}}) is a 2007 Italian [[drama film]] directed by [[Silvio Soldini]]. It was entered into the [[30th Moscow International Film Festival]] where [[Margherita Buy]] won the award for Best Actress.<ref name=\"Moscow2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=2008 |title=30th Moscow International Film Festival (2008) |accessdate=2 June 2013 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421050837/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=2008 |archivedate=21 April 2013  }}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nSet in [[Genoa]], the film concerns the financial struggles and emotional strain that occur after Michele ([[Antonio Albanese]]) loses his job.  He and his wife Elsa ([[Margherita Buy]]) are forced to give up their affluent lifestyle and cope with the tensions of moving into a smaller home, finding new work, and making sacrifices.  \n\n==Cast==\n* [[Margherita Buy]] as Elsa\n* [[Antonio Albanese]] as Michele\n* [[Giuseppe Battiston]] as Vito\n* [[Alba Rohrwacher]] as Alice\n* [[Carla Signoris]] as Nadia\n* [[Fabio Troiano]] as Riki\n* [[Paolo Sassanelli]] as Salviati\n* [[Arnaldo Ninchi]] as Padre di Michele\n* [[Teco Celio]] as Ragionier Terzetti\n* [[Antonio Carlo Francini]] as Luciano\n* [[Carlo Scola]] as Fabrizio\n* [[Alberto Giusta]] as Roberto\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0887732|Days and Clouds}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|days_and_clouds|Days and Clouds}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Days And Clouds}}\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:2007 drama films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Italian drama films]]\n[[Category:Italian-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Silvio Soldini]]\n{{2000s-Italy-film-stub}}\n{{2000s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2007 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Days and Clouds\n| image          = Days and Clouds.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Silvio Soldini]]\n| producer       = Lionello Cerri\n| writer         = Silvio Soldini<br>[[Doriana Leondeff]]<br>[[Francesco Piccolo]]\n| starring       = [[Margherita Buy]]\n| music          = Giovanni Venosta\n| cinematography = Ramiro Civita\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2007|9|12|[[2007 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2007|10|26|Italy|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 118 minutes\n| country        = Italy\n| language       = Italian\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Days and Clouds''''' ({{lang-it|'''Giorni e nuvole'''}}) is a 2007 Italian [[drama film]] directed by [[Silvio Soldini]]. It was entered into the [[30th Moscow International Film Festival]] where [[Margherita Buy]] won the award for Best Actress.<ref name=\"Moscow2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=2008 |title=30th Moscow International Film Festival (2008) |accessdate=2 June 2013 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421050837/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=2008 |archivedate=21 April 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nSet in [[Genoa]], the film concerns the financial struggles and emotional strain that occur after Michele ([[Antonio Albanese]]) loses his job.  He and his wife Elsa ([[Margherita Buy]]) are forced to give up their affluent lifestyle and cope with the tensions of moving into a smaller home, finding new work, and making sacrifices.  \n\n==Cast==\n* [[Margherita Buy]] as Elsa\n* [[Antonio Albanese]] as Michele\n* [[Giuseppe Battiston]] as Vito\n* [[Alba Rohrwacher]] as Alice\n* [[Carla Signoris]] as Nadia\n* [[Fabio Troiano]] as Riki\n* [[Paolo Sassanelli]] as Salviati\n* [[Arnaldo Ninchi]] as Padre di Michele\n* [[Teco Celio]] as Ragionier Terzetti\n* [[Antonio Carlo Francini]] as Luciano\n* [[Carlo Scola]] as Fabrizio\n* [[Alberto Giusta]] as Roberto\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0887732|Days and Clouds}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|days_and_clouds|Days and Clouds}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Days And Clouds}}\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:2007 drama films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Italian drama films]]\n[[Category:Italian-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Silvio Soldini]]\n{{2000s-Italy-film-stub}}\n{{2000s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Days_and_Clouds"}
{"title_page": "Baby Ruth", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Babe Ruth}}\n{{infobox brand\n| logo                   = Baby-Ruth-Wrapper-Small.jpg\n| name                   = Baby Ruth\n| image                  = Baby-Ruth-Split.jpg\n| type                   = [[Confectionery]]\n| currentowner           = [[Ferrara Candy Company]]\n| origin                 = United States\n| introduced             = {{Start date and age|1921|mf=y}}\n| discontinued           = \n| related                = \n| markets                = \n| previousowners         = {{Unbulleted list|[[Curtiss Candy Company]] |[[RJR Nabisco]] |[[Nestl\u00e9]]}}\n| trademarkregistrations = \n| ambassador             = \n| tagline                = \n| website                = {{URL |1=www.babyruth.com}}  \n}}\n'''Baby Ruth''' is an American [[chocolate bar|candy bar]] made of [[peanut]]s, [[caramel]], and milk chocolate-flavored [[nougat]], covered in [[compound chocolate]].<ref name=\"Klein 2014\">{{cite web | last=Klein | first=Christopher | title=Babe Ruth v. Baby Ruth | publisher=[[History (U.S. TV network)|History]] (network) | date=September 25, 2014 | url=http://www.history.com/news/hungry-history/babe-ruth-v-baby-ruth | access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref> It is distributed by the [[Ferrara Candy Company]], a subsidiary of [[Ferrero SpA|Ferrero]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ferrarausa.com/brands.html|title=Brands {{!}} Ferrara Candy Company|website=www.ferrarausa.com|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 1920, the [[Curtiss Candy Company]] refashioned its Kandy Kake into the Baby Ruth, and it became the best-selling confection in the five-cent confectionery category by the late 1920s.<ref name=\"Smith-OCAFD 2007\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GZVweuXhZlkC&pg=PT57|title=The Oxford Companion to American Food and Drink|last=Smith|first=A.F.|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2007|isbn=978-0-19-988576-3|series=Oxford Companions|pages=31\u201332|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Kawash 2013\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2NyTUwbHrGMC&pg=PT134|title=Candy: A Century of Panic and Pleasure|last=Kawash|first=S.|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|year=2013|isbn=978-0-374-71110-8|page=134|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Smith 2012\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7-WcKK01H1cC&pg=PA33|title=Fast Food and Junk Food: An Encyclopedia of What We Love to Eat|last=Smith|first=A.F.|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2012|isbn=978-0-313-39393-8|series=Fast Food and Junk Food: An Encyclopedia of what We Love to Eat|pages=33\u201334|access-date=October 29, 2017|issue=v. 1}}</ref> The bar was a staple of the [[Chicago]]-based company for some seven decades.\n\nCurtiss was purchased by [[Nabisco]] in 1981. In 1990, [[RJR Nabisco]] sold the Curtiss brands to [[Nestl\u00e9]].<ref name=\"zeldes\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.diningchicago.com/blog/2011/06/27/chicagos-baby-ruth/|title=Named for slugger or president's kid, candy is Chicago's baby|last=Zeldes|first=Leah A.|date=2011-06-27|work=Dining Chicago|publisher=Chicago's Restaurant & Entertainment Guide, Inc.|accessdate=2011-06-30}}</ref> Ferrero acquired Nestl\u00e9 USA's confectionery brands, including Baby Ruth, in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20180331005008/en/Ferrero-Completes-Acquisition-Nestl\u00e9-USA\u2019s-Confectionary-Business|title=Ferrero Completes Acquisition of Nestl\u00e9 USA\u2019s Confectionary Business|website=Business Wire|accessdate=7 May 2018}}</ref> Ferrero folded production of the acquired brands into the Ferrara Candy Company.\n\n== Future ==\nFerrara has plans to relaunch Baby Ruth, along with [[100 Grand Bar|100 Grand]], in December 2019. The new recipe will include dry-roasted peanuts grown in the United States, whereas previous version contained peanuts roasted in oil. This will give the new recipe a cleaner peanut flavor profile.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.confectionerynews.com/Article/2019/05/24/As-Kellogg-Keebler-deal-closes-Ferrara-poised-to-reach-3bn-in-sales|title=As Kellogg-Keebler deal closes, Ferrara poised to reach $3bn in sales|last=confectionerynews.com|website=confectionerynews.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Portsmouth - Post Office and General Store - inside - 01 cropped.jpg|thumb|Box of [[Curtiss Candy Company|Curtiss]]' Baby Ruth candy bars at a General Store in [[Portsmouth, North Carolina]].]]\n\nAlthough the name of the candy bar sounds like the name of the famous [[baseball]] player [[Babe Ruth]], the [[Curtiss Candy Company]] traditionally claimed that it was named after President [[Grover Cleveland]]'s daughter, [[Ruth Cleveland]].<ref name=\"Kawash 2013\"/><ref name=\"Smith 2012\"/> The candy maker, located on the same street as [[Wrigley Field]], named the bar \"Baby Ruth\" in 1921, as Babe Ruth's fame was on the rise, 24 years after Cleveland had left the [[White House]], and 17 years after his daughter, Ruth, had died. The company did not negotiate an endorsement deal with Ruth, and many saw the company's story about the origin of the name to be a devious way to avoid having to pay the baseball player any [[royalties]]. Curtiss successfully shut down a rival bar that was approved by, and named for, Ruth, on the grounds that the names were too similar.<ref>Case of ''George H. Ruth Candy Co. v. Curtiss Candy Co'', 49 F.2d 1033 (1931), [http://www.snopes.com/business/names/babyruth.asp Urban Legends Reference Pages: Baby Ruth<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn the trivia book series ''Imponderables'', David Feldman reports the standard story about the bar being named for Grover Cleveland's daughter, with additional information that ties it to the President: \"The trademark was patterned exactly after the engraved lettering of the name used on a medallion struck for the Chicago [[World's Columbian Exposition]] in 1893, and picturing the President, his wife, and daughter Baby Ruth.\u201d However, this may have been an after-the-fact covering maneuver.<ref>''What Are Hyenas Laughing At, Anyway?'' (1995), p.&nbsp;84.</ref> He also cites ''More Misinformation'', by Tom Burnam: \"Burnam concluded that the candy bar was named ... after the granddaughter of Mr. and Mrs. George Williamson, candy makers who developed the original formula and sold it to Curtiss.\" (Williamson had also sold the \"[[Oh Henry!]]\" formula to Curtiss around that time.) The writeup goes on to note that marketing the product as being named for a company executive's granddaughter would likely have been less successful, hence their \"official\" story.<ref>''How Do Astronauts Scratch an Itch?'' (1996), p.&nbsp;288\u2013289.</ref>\n\nHowever, David Mikkelson of [[Snopes|Snopes.com]] denies the claim that the Williamsons invented the recipe, as George Williamson was head of the Williamson Candy Company, producers of the Oh Henry! bar. He continues to say that \"the Baby Ruth bar came about when Otto Schnering, founder of the Curtiss Candy Company, made some alterations to his company's first candy offering, a confection known as 'Kandy Kake.'\"<ref>''Do Elephants Jump?'' (2004), p.&nbsp;264\u2013265.</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\n[[File:Wrigley Baby Ruth.JPG|thumb|left|180px|The Baby Ruth sign at [[Wrigley Field]]]]\n\nTo promote the candy, company founder Otto Schnering chartered a plane in 1923 to drop thousands of Baby Ruth bars, each with its own miniature parachute, over the city of [[Pittsburgh]].<ref name=\"Smith 2012\"/><ref name=\"zeldes\" /> Thereafter, Schnering performed the parachute drops in various cities in over forty states.<ref name=\"Smith 2012\"/>\n\nIn 1929, the Curtiss Candy Company sponsored ''The Baby Ruth Hour'', a [[CBS Radio]] program.<ref name=\"Smith 2012\" />\n\nAs if to tweak their own official denial of the name's origin, after [[Babe Ruth's called shot|Babe Ruth's \u201ccalled shot\u201d]] at [[Wrigley Field]] in the 1932 [[World Series]], Curtiss installed an illuminated advertising sign for Baby Ruth on the roof of one of the flats across Sheffield Avenue, near where Ruth's home run ball had landed in center field.<ref>{{cite book | title=Wrigley Field | publisher=Potomac Books | year=2006 | isbn=978-1-61234-411-9 | url=https://archive.org/details/wrigleyfieldunau0000shea_d1m0 | url-access=registration | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=[https://archive.org/details/wrigleyfieldunau0000shea_d1m0/page/254 254]}}</ref> The sign stood for some four decades before being removed.<ref>{{cite book | last=Johnson | first=S. | title=Chicago Cubs Yesterday & Today | publisher=MVP Books | year=2008 | isbn=978-0-7603-3246-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HPtkHbGUOtAC&pg=PA113 | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=113}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Nabisco paid $100,000 for the [[product placement]] of Baby Ruth to appear in the film ''[[The Goonies]]''.<ref>{{cite book | last=Cones | first=J.W. | title=The Feature Film Distribution Deal: A Critical Analysis of the Single Most Important Film Industry Agreement | publisher=Southern Illinois University Press | year=1997 | isbn=978-0-8093-2082-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EoeJ7VmwnDIC&pg=PA60 | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=60}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, the company sponsored [[Bill Davis Racing]]'s [[NASCAR Busch Grand National Series]] #1 Ford for future [[NASCAR]] superstar [[Jeff Gordon]]. The following year, the sponsorship moved to [[Jeff Burton]]'s #8 Ford.\n\nIn 1995, a company representing the Ruth estate licensed his name and likeness for use in a Baby Ruth marketing campaign.<ref name=\"ny_times_estate\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/06/business/worldbusiness/06iht-web.0606ruth.1900800.html?_r=1|title=Baseball adopts a candy, whatever it is named for \u2013 Business \u2013 International Herald Tribune|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|date=June 6, 2006|work=New York Times|accessdate=2009-06-23}}</ref>\n\nOn p.&nbsp;34 of the spring, 2007, edition of the [[Chicago Cubs]] game program, there is a full-page ad showing a partially unwrapped Baby Ruth in front of the Wrigley ivy, with the caption, \"The official candy bar of major league baseball, and proud sponsor of the Chicago Cubs.\"\n\nContinuing the baseball-oriented theme, during the summer and post-season of the 2007 season, a TV ad for the candy bar showed an entire stadium (identified as [[Dodger Stadium]]) filled with people munching Baby Ruths, and thus having to hum rather than singing along with \"[[Take Me Out to the Ball Game]]\" during the [[seventh-inning stretch]].\n\n==Ingredients==\n[[File:Baby Ruth.jpg|thumb|A Baby Ruth bar]]\nThe original flavor U.S. edition, listed by weight in decreasing order, contains [[sugar]], [[Roasting|roasted]] [[peanut]]s, [[corn syrup]], [[partially hydrogenated]] [[Palm oil|palm kernel]] and [[coconut oil]],<ref name=\"Gomstyn 2008\">{{cite web | last=Gomstyn | first=Alice | title=Chocolate Lovers Pained by Candy Changes | publisher=ABC News | date=November 14, 2008 | url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/IndustryInfo/story?id=5689239&page=1 | access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref> nonfat [[milk]], [[Cocoa solids|cocoa]], [[high-fructose corn syrup]] and less than 1% of [[Glycerol|glycerin]], [[whey]] (from milk), [[dextrose]], [[salt]], [[egg]], [[monoglyceride]], [[Soybean|soy]] [[lecithin]], [[Soybean|soybean oil]], natural and artificial [[flavor]]s, [[carrageenan]], [[Tert-Butylhydroquinone|TBHQ]], [[citric acid]] (to preserve freshness) and [[caramel]] color.<ref>{{cite book | title=Congressional Record, V. 147, PT. 18, December 11, 2001 to December 12, 2001 | publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office | year=2006 | isbn=978-0-16-075591-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fEE_3udJWDIC&pg=PA2131 | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=2131}}</ref>\n\n==Sizes==\nIn addition to the single 2.1-ounce (59.5-gram) bar (sold in packages as Full Size), Baby Ruth is also sold in a {{convert|3.7|oz|g|adj=on}} (King Size), and in packages of Fun Size and Miniatures.<ref name=\"Gomstyn 2008\"/><ref>{{cite book | author=Nutribase | title=The NutriBase Guide to Fat & Fiber in Your Food | publisher=Avery | year=2001 | isbn=978-1-58333-111-8 | url=https://archive.org/details/nutribaseguideto00nutr | url-access=registration | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=[https://archive.org/details/nutribaseguideto00nutr/page/116 116]}}</ref>\n\n==Related products==\nNestl\u00e9 produces a Baby Ruth [[ice cream|ice cream bar]] with a [[Types of chocolate|milk chocolate]] coating, [[chocolate]]-covered peanuts, and a [[vanilla]]-and-[[nougat]] flavored [[ice cream]] center.<ref>{{cite book | last=MacInerney | first=D.M.L. | last2=Ryan | first2=C. | title=Ed. F. Kruse of Blue Bell Creameries | publisher=Texas A&M University Press | year=2016 | isbn=978-1-62349-363-9 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ahRDDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA79 | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=79}}</ref> Nestl\u00e9 also produces [[Crisp (chocolate bar)|Baby Ruth Crisp]] bars, which are chocolate-covered wafer [[cookie]]s, with a caramel-flavored cream and crushed peanuts.  This is part of a line of Nestl\u00e9 products under the Crisp name, including [[Nestl\u00e9 Crunch]] Crisp and [[Butterfinger]] Crisp.\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe Baby Ruth bar is infamously featured in a scene in the 1980 movie ''[[Caddyshack]]'' that takes place at a pool party.<ref>{{cite book | last=Praeger | first=D. | title=Poop Culture: How America Is Shaped by Its Grossest National Product | publisher=Feral House | year=2007 | isbn=978-1-932595-21-5 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iHDXlUbkJWQC&pg=PA128 | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=128}}</ref> Two teenage girls are sitting at poolside and one girl offers to share the tasty confection with her friend, when a third teen \u2014 a boy \u2014 asks for a piece of the candy and the girls refuse his request. The boy then tries to take the candy bar from the first girl, thereby accidentally knocking it into the pool, much to the young ladies' annoyance. Thinking someone had [[Defecation|defecated]] in the pool due to the candy's perceived resemblance to [[Feces|human feces]], all the partygoers make a mad scramble out of the pool. When Carl Spackler ([[Bill Murray]]) is cleaning out the pool afterward and recognizes the offending item as a Baby Ruth bar (\"It's no big deal!\"), he takes a bite out of it, disgusting the country club's co-founder and his wife (played by [[Ted Knight]] and [[Lois Kibbee]]), who still believe it to be feces.\n\nBaby Ruth was used in the American film ''[[The Goonies]]''<ref>{{cite book | last=Molinari | first=M. | last2=Kamm | first2=J. | title=Oops!: Movie Mistakes That Made the Cut | publisher=Citadel Press | year=2002 | isbn=978-0-8065-2319-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S8en3TIqmeQC&pg=PA86 | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=86}}</ref> by Chunk to befriend Sloth.\n\nIn the film ''[[The Sandlot]]'', Scotty Smalls (after using his stepfather's Babe Ruth-autographed baseball in a game and wanting to get it back after he hit it over the fence into a backyard) mistakenly tells his friends that it was autographed by \"Baby Ruth\"; his friends knew what he meant to say and shout \"BABE RUTH!\" before running to the fence to see the ball before it is taken away by a demonic dog that they call \"the Beast\".\n\nIn the film ''The Mighty'' both Max and Kevin are awarded Baby Ruth bars for taking care of a problem in a local store.\n\nIn the film ''[[Hellboy (2004 film)|Hellboy]]'', a Baby Ruth bar is used to lure and  mollify the infant Hellboy when he is discovered after the destruction of the Nazi portal.\n\nA popular song from the year 1956 was \"[[A Rose and a Baby Ruth]],\" written by [[John D. Loudermilk]] and recorded by [[George Hamilton IV]].<ref>{{cite book | last=Coston | first=D. | title=North Carolina Musicians: Photographs and Conversations | publisher=McFarland | year=2013 | isbn=978-0-7864-7461-5 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gmIsAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA110 | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=110}}</ref>\n\nIn the movie ''[[Four Brothers (film)|Four Brothers]]'', Angel Mercer (played by [[Tyrese Gibson]]) offers to give a local kid playing baseball an entire box of Baby Ruth bars if he helps Angel by creating a distraction so Angel can ambush a dirty cop at his home.\n\nIn the television series ''[[Friends]]'', Rachel Green (played by [[Jennifer Aniston]]) and Ross Geller (played by [[David Schwimmer]]) are discussing baby names, almost settling on the name Ruth until Rachel excitedly says \"Yes! We're having a little baby Ruth...\" and they realise the obvious brand recognition joke.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of chocolate bar brands]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=Sweets: A History of Candy |first=Tim |last=Richardson |authorlink=Tim Richardson (writer) |year=2003 |location=New York |publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing]] |isbn=978-1582343075}}\n* {{cite web | title=Baby Ruth, Butterfinger and Crunch are going natural | website=The Washington Post | date=February 18, 2015 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/02/18/baby-ruth-butterfinger-and-crunch-are-going-natural/ | ref={{sfnref | Washington Post | 2015}} | access-date=October 29, 2017}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Baby Ruth}}\n* [http://www.babyruth.com Baby Ruth website]\n* [http://www.snopes.com/business/names/babyruth.asp Snopes.com article] \u2013 about the Baby Ruth naming controversy\n\n\n[[Category:Brand name confectionery]]\n[[Category:Chocolate bars]]\n[[Category:Ice cream brands]]\n[[Category:Ferrero brands]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1921]]\n[[Category:Peanut dishes]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Babe Ruth]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Babe Ruth}}\n{{infobox brand\n| logo                   = Baby-Ruth-Wrapper-Small.jpg\n| name                   = Baby Ruth\n| image                  = Baby-Ruth-Split.jpg\n| type                   = [[Confectionery]]\n| currentowner           = [[Ferrara Candy Company]]\n| origin                 = United States\n| introduced             = {{Start date and age|1921|mf=y}}\n| discontinued           = \n| related                = \n| markets                = \n| previousowners         = {{Unbulleted list|[[Curtiss Candy Company]] |[[RJR Nabisco]] |[[Nestl\u00e9]]}}\n| trademarkregistrations = \n| ambassador             = \n| tagline                = \n| website                = {{URL |1=www.babyruth.com}}  \n}}\n'''Baby Ruth''' is an American [[chocolate bar|candy bar]] made of [[peanut]]s, [[caramel]], and milk chocolate-flavored [[nougat]], covered in [[compound chocolate]].<ref name=\"Klein 2014\">{{cite web | last=Klein | first=Christopher | title=Babe Ruth v. Baby Ruth | publisher=[[History (U.S. TV network)|History]] (network) | date=September 25, 2014 | url=http://www.history.com/news/hungry-history/babe-ruth-v-baby-ruth | access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref> It is distributed by the [[Ferrara Candy Company]], a subsidiary of [[Ferrero SpA|Ferrero]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ferrarausa.com/brands.html|title=Brands {{!}} Ferrara Candy Company|website=www.ferrarausa.com|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 1920, the [[Curtiss Candy Company]] refashioned its Kandy Kake into the Baby Ruth, and it became the best-selling confection in the five-cent confectionery category by the late 1920s.<ref name=\"Smith-OCAFD 2007\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GZVweuXhZlkC&pg=PT57|title=The Oxford Companion to American Food and Drink|last=Smith|first=A.F.|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2007|isbn=978-0-19-988576-3|series=Oxford Companions|pages=31\u201332|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Kawash 2013\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2NyTUwbHrGMC&pg=PT134|title=Candy: A Century of Panic and Pleasure|last=Kawash|first=S.|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|year=2013|isbn=978-0-374-71110-8|page=134|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Smith 2012\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7-WcKK01H1cC&pg=PA33|title=Fast Food and Junk Food: An Encyclopedia of What We Love to Eat|last=Smith|first=A.F.|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2012|isbn=978-0-313-39393-8|series=Fast Food and Junk Food: An Encyclopedia of what We Love to Eat|pages=33\u201334|access-date=October 29, 2017|issue=v. 1}}</ref> The bar was a staple of the [[Chicago]]-based company for some seven decades.\n\nCurtiss was purchased by [[Nabisco]] in 1981. In 1990, [[RJR Nabisco]] sold the Curtiss brands to [[Nestl\u00e9]].<ref name=\"zeldes\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.diningchicago.com/blog/2011/06/27/chicagos-baby-ruth/|title=Named for slugger or president's kid, candy is Chicago's baby|last=Zeldes|first=Leah A.|date=2011-06-27|work=Dining Chicago|publisher=Chicago's Restaurant & Entertainment Guide, Inc.|accessdate=2011-06-30}}</ref> Ferrero acquired Nestl\u00e9 USA's confectionery brands, including Baby Ruth, in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20180331005008/en/Ferrero-Completes-Acquisition-Nestl\u00e9-USA\u2019s-Confectionary-Business|title=Ferrero Completes Acquisition of Nestl\u00e9 USA\u2019s Confectionary Business|website=Business Wire|accessdate=7 May 2018}}</ref> Ferrero folded production of the acquired brands into the Ferrara Candy Company.\n\n== Future ==\nFerrara has plans to relaunch Baby Ruth, along with [[100 Grand Bar|100 Grand]], in December 2019. The new recipe will include dry-roasted peanuts grown in the United States, whereas previous version contained peanuts roasted in oil. This will give the new recipe a cleaner peanut flavor profile.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.confectionerynews.com/Article/2019/05/24/As-Kellogg-Keebler-deal-closes-Ferrara-poised-to-reach-3bn-in-sales|title=As Kellogg-Keebler deal closes, Ferrara poised to reach $3bn in sales|last=confectionerynews.com|website=confectionerynews.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Portsmouth - Post Office and General Store - inside - 01 cropped.jpg|thumb|Box of [[Curtiss Candy Company|Curtiss]]' Baby Ruth candy bars at a General Store in [[Portsmouth, North Carolina]].]]\n\nAlthough the name of the candy bar sounds like the name of the famous [[baseball]] player [[Babe Ruth]], the [[Curtiss Candy Company]] traditionally claimed that it was named after President [[Grover Cleveland]]'s daughter, [[Ruth Cleveland]].<ref name=\"Kawash 2013\"/><ref name=\"Smith 2012\"/> The candy maker, located on the same street as [[Wrigley Field]], named the bar \"Baby Ruth\" in 1921, as Babe Ruth's fame was on the rise, 24 years after Cleveland had left the [[White House]], and 17 years after his daughter, Ruth, had died. The company did not negotiate an endorsement deal with Ruth, and many saw the company's story about the origin of the name to be a devious way to avoid having to pay the baseball player any [[royalties]]. Curtiss successfully shut down a rival bar that was approved by, and named for, Ruth, on the grounds that the names were too similar.<ref>Case of ''George H. Ruth Candy Co. v. Curtiss Candy Co'', 49 F.2d 1033 (1931), [http://www.snopes.com/business/names/babyruth.asp Urban Legends Reference Pages: Baby Ruth<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn the trivia book series ''Imponderables'', David Feldman reports the standard story about the bar being named for Grover Cleveland's daughter, with additional information that ties it to the President: \"The trademark was patterned exactly after the engraved lettering of the name used on a medallion struck for the Chicago [[World's Columbian Exposition]] in 1893, and picturing the President, his wife, and daughter Baby Ruth.\u201d However, this may have been an after-the-fact covering maneuver.<ref>''What Are Hyenas Laughing At, Anyway?'' (1995), p.&nbsp;84.</ref> He also cites ''More Misinformation'', by Tom Burnam: \"Burnam concluded that the candy bar was named ... after the granddaughter of Mr. and Mrs. George Williamson, candy makers who developed the original formula and sold it to Curtiss.\" (Williamson had also sold the \"[[Oh Henry!]]\" formula to Curtiss around that time.) The writeup goes on to note that marketing the product as being named for a company executive's granddaughter would likely have been less successful, hence their \"official\" story.<ref>''How Do Astronauts Scratch an Itch?'' (1996), p.&nbsp;288-289.</ref>\n\nHowever, David Mikkelson of [[Snopes|Snopes.com]] denies the claim that the Williamsons invented the recipe, as George Williamson was head of the Williamson Candy Company, producers of the Oh Henry! bar. He continues to say that \"the Baby Ruth bar came about when Otto Schnering, founder of the Curtiss Candy Company, made some alterations to his company's first candy offering, a confection known as 'Kandy Kake.'\"<ref>''Do Elephants Jump?'' (2004), p.&nbsp;264-265.</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\n[[File:Wrigley Baby Ruth.JPG|thumb|left|180px|The Baby Ruth sign at [[Wrigley Field]]]]\n\nTo promote the candy, company founder Otto Schnering chartered a plane in 1923 to drop thousands of Baby Ruth bars, each with its own miniature parachute, over the city of [[Pittsburgh]].<ref name=\"Smith 2012\"/><ref name=\"zeldes\" /> Thereafter, Schnering performed the parachute drops in various cities in over forty states.<ref name=\"Smith 2012\"/>\n\nIn 1929, the Curtiss Candy Company sponsored ''The Baby Ruth Hour'', a [[CBS Radio]] program.<ref name=\"Smith 2012\" />\n\nAs if to tweak their own official denial of the name's origin, after [[Babe Ruth's called shot|Babe Ruth's \u201ccalled shot\u201d]] at [[Wrigley Field]] in the 1932 [[World Series]], Curtiss installed an illuminated advertising sign for Baby Ruth on the roof of one of the flats across Sheffield Avenue, near where Ruth's home run ball had landed in center field.<ref>{{cite book | title=Wrigley Field | publisher=Potomac Books | year=2006 | isbn=978-1-61234-411-9 | url=https://archive.org/details/wrigleyfieldunau0000shea_d1m0 | url-access=registration | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=[https://archive.org/details/wrigleyfieldunau0000shea_d1m0/page/254 254]}}</ref> The sign stood for some four decades before being removed.<ref>{{cite book | last=Johnson | first=S. | title=Chicago Cubs Yesterday & Today | publisher=MVP Books | year=2008 | isbn=978-0-7603-3246-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HPtkHbGUOtAC&pg=PA113 | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=113}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Nabisco paid $100,000 for the [[product placement]] of Baby Ruth to appear in the film ''[[The Goonies]]''.<ref>{{cite book | last=Cones | first=J.W. | title=The Feature Film Distribution Deal: A Critical Analysis of the Single Most Important Film Industry Agreement | publisher=Southern Illinois University Press | year=1997 | isbn=978-0-8093-2082-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EoeJ7VmwnDIC&pg=PA60 | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=60}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, the company sponsored [[Bill Davis Racing]]'s [[NASCAR Busch Grand National Series]] #1 Ford for future [[NASCAR]] superstar [[Jeff Gordon]]. The following year, the sponsorship moved to [[Jeff Burton]]'s #8 Ford.\n\nIn 1995, a company representing the Ruth estate licensed his name and likeness for use in a Baby Ruth marketing campaign.<ref name=\"ny_times_estate\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/06/business/worldbusiness/06iht-web.0606ruth.1900800.html?_r=1|title=Baseball adopts a candy, whatever it is named for - Business - International Herald Tribune|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|date=June 6, 2006|work=New York Times|accessdate=2009-06-23}}</ref>\n\nOn p.&nbsp;34 of the spring, 2007, edition of the [[Chicago Cubs]] game program, there is a full-page ad showing a partially unwrapped Baby Ruth in front of the Wrigley ivy, with the caption, \"The official candy bar of major league baseball, and proud sponsor of the Chicago Cubs.\"\n\nContinuing the baseball-oriented theme, during the summer and post-season of the 2007 season, a TV ad for the candy bar showed an entire stadium (identified as [[Dodger Stadium]]) filled with people munching Baby Ruths, and thus having to hum rather than singing along with \"[[Take Me Out to the Ball Game]]\" during the [[seventh-inning stretch]].\n\n==Ingredients==\n[[File:Baby Ruth.jpg|thumb|A Baby Ruth bar]]\nThe original flavor U.S. edition, listed by weight in decreasing order, contains [[sugar]], [[Roasting|roasted]] [[peanut]]s, [[corn syrup]], [[partially hydrogenated]] [[Palm oil|palm kernel]] and [[coconut oil]],<ref name=\"Gomstyn 2008\">{{cite web | last=Gomstyn | first=Alice | title=Chocolate Lovers Pained by Candy Changes | publisher=ABC News | date=November 14, 2008 | url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/IndustryInfo/story?id=5689239&page=1 | access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref> nonfat [[milk]], [[Cocoa solids|cocoa]], [[high-fructose corn syrup]] and less than 1% of [[Glycerol|glycerin]], [[whey]] (from milk), [[dextrose]], [[salt]], [[egg]], [[monoglyceride]], [[Soybean|soy]] [[lecithin]], [[Soybean|soybean oil]], natural and artificial [[flavor]]s, [[carrageenan]], [[Tert-Butylhydroquinone|TBHQ]], [[citric acid]] (to preserve freshness) and [[caramel]] color.<ref>{{cite book | title=Congressional Record, V. 147, PT. 18, December 11, 2001 to December 12, 2001 | publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office | year=2006 | isbn=978-0-16-075591-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fEE_3udJWDIC&pg=PA2131 | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=2131}}</ref>\n\n==Sizes==\nIn addition to the single 2.1-ounce (59.5-gram) bar (sold in packages as Full Size), Baby Ruth is also sold in a {{convert|3.7|oz|g|adj=on}} (King Size), and in packages of Fun Size and Miniatures.<ref name=\"Gomstyn 2008\"/><ref>{{cite book | author=Nutribase | title=The NutriBase Guide to Fat & Fiber in Your Food | publisher=Avery | year=2001 | isbn=978-1-58333-111-8 | url=https://archive.org/details/nutribaseguideto00nutr | url-access=registration | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=[https://archive.org/details/nutribaseguideto00nutr/page/116 116]}}</ref>\n\n==Related products==\nNestl\u00e9 produces a Baby Ruth [[ice cream|ice cream bar]] with a [[Types of chocolate|milk chocolate]] coating, [[chocolate]]-covered peanuts, and a [[vanilla]]-and-[[nougat]] flavored [[ice cream]] center.<ref>{{cite book | last=MacInerney | first=D.M.L. | last2=Ryan | first2=C. | title=Ed. F. Kruse of Blue Bell Creameries | publisher=Texas A&M University Press | year=2016 | isbn=978-1-62349-363-9 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ahRDDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA79 | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=79}}</ref> Nestl\u00e9 also produces [[Crisp (chocolate bar)|Baby Ruth Crisp]] bars, which are chocolate-covered wafer [[cookie]]s, with a caramel-flavored cream and crushed peanuts.  This is part of a line of Nestl\u00e9 products under the Crisp name, including [[Nestl\u00e9 Crunch]] Crisp and [[Butterfinger]] Crisp.\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe Baby Ruth bar is infamously featured in a scene in the 1980 movie ''[[Caddyshack]]'' that takes place at a pool party.<ref>{{cite book | last=Praeger | first=D. | title=Poop Culture: How America Is Shaped by Its Grossest National Product | publisher=Feral House | year=2007 | isbn=978-1-932595-21-5 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iHDXlUbkJWQC&pg=PA128 | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=128}}</ref> Two teenage girls are sitting at poolside and one girl offers to share the tasty confection with her friend, when a third teen \u2014 a boy \u2014 asks for a piece of the candy and the girls refuse his request. The boy then tries to take the candy bar from the first girl, thereby accidentally knocking it into the pool, much to the young ladies' annoyance. Thinking someone had [[Defecation|defecated]] in the pool due to the candy's perceived resemblance to [[Feces|human feces]], all the partygoers make a mad scramble out of the pool. When Carl Spackler ([[Bill Murray]]) is cleaning out the pool afterward and recognizes the offending item as a Baby Ruth bar (\"It's no big deal!\"), he takes a bite out of it, disgusting the country club's co-founder and his wife (played by [[Ted Knight]] and [[Lois Kibbee]]), who still believe it to be feces.\n\nBaby Ruth was used in the American film ''[[The Goonies]]''<ref>{{cite book | last=Molinari | first=M. | last2=Kamm | first2=J. | title=Oops!: Movie Mistakes That Made the Cut | publisher=Citadel Press | year=2002 | isbn=978-0-8065-2319-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S8en3TIqmeQC&pg=PA86 | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=86}}</ref> by Chunk to befriend Sloth.\n\nIn the film ''[[The Sandlot]]'', Scotty Smalls (after using his stepfather's Babe Ruth-autographed baseball in a game and wanting to get it back after he hit it over the fence into a backyard) mistakenly tells his friends that it was autographed by \"Baby Ruth\"; his friends knew what he meant to say and shout \"BABE RUTH!\" before running to the fence to see the ball before it is taken away by a demonic dog that they call \"the Beast\".\n\nIn the film ''The Mighty'' both Max and Kevin are awarded Baby Ruth bars for taking care of a problem in a local store.\n\nIn the film ''[[Hellboy (2004 film)|Hellboy]]'', a Baby Ruth bar is used to lure and  mollify the infant Hellboy when he is discovered after the destruction of the Nazi portal.\n\nA popular song from the year 1956 was \"[[A Rose and a Baby Ruth]],\" written by [[John D. Loudermilk]] and recorded by [[George Hamilton IV]].<ref>{{cite book | last=Coston | first=D. | title=North Carolina Musicians: Photographs and Conversations | publisher=McFarland | year=2013 | isbn=978-0-7864-7461-5 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gmIsAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA110 | access-date=October 29, 2017 | page=110}}</ref>\n\nIn the movie ''[[Four Brothers (film)|Four Brothers]]'', Angel Mercer (played by [[Tyrese Gibson]]) offers to give a local kid playing baseball an entire box of Baby Ruth bars if he helps Angel by creating a distraction so Angel can ambush a dirty cop at his home.\n\nIn the television series ''[[Friends]]'', Rachel Green (played by [[Jennifer Aniston]]) and Ross Geller (played by [[David Schwimmer]]) are discussing baby names, almost settling on the name Ruth until Rachel excitedly says \"Yes! We're having a little baby Ruth...\" and they realise the obvious brand recognition joke.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of chocolate bar brands]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=Sweets: A History of Candy |first=Tim |last=Richardson |authorlink=Tim Richardson (writer) |year=2003 |location=New York |publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing]] |isbn=978-1582343075}}\n* {{cite web | title=Baby Ruth, Butterfinger and Crunch are going natural | website=The Washington Post | date=February 18, 2015 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/02/18/baby-ruth-butterfinger-and-crunch-are-going-natural/ | ref={{sfnref | Washington Post | 2015}} | access-date=October 29, 2017}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Baby Ruth}}\n* [http://www.babyruth.com Baby Ruth website]\n* [http://www.snopes.com/business/names/babyruth.asp Snopes.com article] \u2013 about the Baby Ruth naming controversy\n\n\n[[Category:Brand name confectionery]]\n[[Category:Chocolate bars]]\n[[Category:Ice cream brands]]\n[[Category:Ferrero brands]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1921]]\n[[Category:Peanut dishes]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Babe Ruth]]\n", "name_user": "Dave.Dunford", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baby_Ruth"}
{"title_page": "Symon Sadik", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Symon Sadik\n| image              = Symon Sadik (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Symon in 2018\n| other_names        = Gentle Star\n| birth_date         = 30 August 1985\n(Age 34 years)\n| birth_place        = Kalapara, [[Kishoreganj]], [[Bangladesh]]\n| education          = [[Kishoregonj Government Boys' High School]]\n| occupation         = \u2022 [[Film Actor]]\n\u2022 [[Model (person)|Model]]\n\u2022 [[Politician]]\n\u2022 [[Assistant director]]\n| yearsactive        = 2012\u2013present\n| notable_works      = \u2022 [[Ji Hujur]] \n\u2022 [[PoraMon]]\n\u2022 Er Beshi Valobasha Jay Na\n\u2022 Tomar kache Rini \n\u2022 Chupi Chupi Prem\n\u2022 [[Black Money]] \n\u2022 Mayabini\n\u2022 Tui Amar \n\u2022 [[Jannat (2018 film)]]\n| style              = \u2022 [[Romance film|Romantic]]\n\u2022 [[Comedy]]\n\u2022 [[Action film|Action]]\n\u2022 [[Drama]]\n| height             = 1.73 m\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Deepa Sadik|2014}}\n| partner            = Mohammed Sadikur Rahman, Umme Kulsum\n| children           = 2\n| awards             = \u2022 Bioscope Borsho-Sera Awards in (2013)\n\n\u2022 [[Babisas Award]] for Featured Actor Male in (2016)\n\n\u2022 [[Bangladesh National Film Award for Best Actor]] (2018)\n| nationality        = [[Bangladeshi]]\n}}  \n\n'''Symon Sadik''' is a Bangladeshi film Actor Known for his Works in [[Dhallywood|Dhallywood Cinema]]. And He was an [[assistant director|Assistant Director]] and worked with [[Zakir Hossain Raju]]. He made his debut as a lead in the 2012 Bangladeshi film ''[[Ji Hujur]], Directed by [[Zakir Hossain Raju]], And opposite [[Sara Zerin]]. And his second film [[PoraMon]], Directed by [[Zakir Hossain Raju]] and opposite [[Mahiya Mahi]]. And he won Bioscope Borsho-Sera Awards for Best acting in [[PoraMon]].'' And He also won [[Bangladesh National Film Award for Best Actor]] for his role in the film ''[[Jannat (2018 film)|Jannat]]'' (2018).\n\n==Career==\n[[Symon Sadik]] was born on August 30, 1985, at Kalapara, Kishoreganj, Bangladesh. He rose up in the Kishoreganj Sadar. [[Symon Sadik|Symon]] passed SSC from Kishoreganj Govt. Boys School. He was so much passionate about media arena from early childhood and eventually participated in the Super Hero and Heroin competition organized by NTV.\n\n[[Symon Sadik]] and [[Sara Zerin]]  started in 2012 with director Zakir Hossain Raju in [[Ji Hujur|Ji Huzur]] movie. Later, he was introduced to the audience by starring in the successful movie [[PoraMon]] in (2013). [[Symon Sadik]] got his breakthrough in the film [[PoraMon]]. And he also acted in Bangladeshi film Er beshi Valobasha Jay Na (2013), Tui Shudhu Amar, Tomar Kache Rini, 16 Ana Prem, Shopno Chowa in (2014), Chupi Chupi Prem, Black money, Action Jasmine in (2015),Chokher Dekha, Pure Jay Mon, Matir Pori, Ojante Valobasha in (2016), Mayabini, Khash Zamin, Tui Amar in (2017), And He was acted opposite [[Mahiya Mahi]] in the [[Jannat (2018 film)|Jannat]] film on 2018. He was awarded the [[Bangladesh National Film Award for Best Actor]] in the category for his outstanding performance in the film [[Jannat (2018 film)|Jannat]] and he also acted in \"Matal\" movie in (2018)   \n\nAnd  His upcoming movies is [[Ananda Ashru|Ananda Ashro]] (2020) Directed by [[Mostafizur Rahman Manik]] with same team of successful movie [[Jannat (2018 film)|Jannat (2018)]], There was a movie made under the same name [[Anondo Osru|Anondo osru]] in (1997) starring [[Salman Shah (actor)|Salman Shah]] and [[Shabnur]], But there is no similarity in the story of these two films.   \n\nAnd Nodir Buke Chand with opposite [[Pori Moni|PoriMoni]] and Amar Ma Amar Beheshto in (2020)   \n\n==Filmography ==\n'''Key''' \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|{{Dagger|alt=films that have not yet been released}}\n|Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Film\n!Role\n!Director\n!Co-Star\n!Notes\n|-\n| ro